CONTRIBUTING.md
     1→# Contributing
     2→
     3→Welcome stranger!
    10→## Issue assignment
    11→
    12→**:warning: Important :warning:**
    19→## Issues to work on
    20→
    21→If you are starting out, you might be interested in the
    22→[E-Easy issues](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues?q=is%3Aopen+is%3Aissue+label%3AE-Easy).
    23→Those are issues that are considered more straightforward for beginners to Rust or the codebase itself.
    24→These issues can be a good launching pad for more involved issues.
    25→Easy tasks for a first time contribution include documentation improvements, new tests, examples, updating dependencies, etc.
    44→## Building mdBook
    45→
    46→mdBook builds on stable Rust, if you want to build mdBook from source, here are the steps to follow:
    59→## Code quality
    60→
    61→We love code quality and Rust has some excellent tools to assist you with contributions.
    63→### Formatting code with rustfmt
    64→
    65→Before you make your Pull Request to the project, please run it through the `rustfmt` utility.
    66→This will ensure we have good quality source code that is better for us all to maintain.
    87→### Finding issues with clippy
    88→
    89→[Clippy](https://doc.rust-lang.org/clippy/) is a code analyser/linter detecting mistakes, and therefore helps to improve your code.
    90→Like formatting your code with `rustfmt`, running clippy regularly and before your Pull Request will help us maintain awesome code.
   101→## Change requirements
   102→
   103→Please consider the following when making a change:
   126→## Tests
   127→
   128→The main test harness is described in the [testsuite documentation](tests/testsuite/README.md). There are several different commands to run different kinds of tests:
   153→## Making a pull-request
   154→
   155→When you feel comfortable that your changes could be integrated into mdBook, you can create a pull-request on GitHub.
   156→One of the core maintainers will then approve the changes or request some changes before it gets merged.
   160→## Browser compatibility and testing
   161→
   162→Currently we don't have a strict browser compatibility matrix due to our limited resources.
   163→We generally strive to keep mdBook compatible with a relatively recent browser on all of the most major platforms.
   164→That is, supporting Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge on Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS, and Android.
   165→If possible, do your best to avoid breaking older browser releases.
   190→### Checking changes in `.js` files
   191→
   192→The `.js` files source code is checked using [`eslint`](https://eslint.org/). This is a linter (just like `clippy` in Rust)
   193→for the Javascript language. You can install it with `npm` by running the following command:
   205→## Updating highlight.js
