    20→A simple approach would be to use the popular `curl` CLI tool to download the executable:
    39→### Building from source
    40→
    41→Building from source will require having Rust installed.
    42→Some services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    67→## Running tests
    68→
    69→You may want to run tests using [`mdbook test`] every time you push a change or create a pull request.
    70→This can be used to validate Rust code examples in the book.
    83→## Deploying
    84→
    85→You may want to automatically deploy your book.
    86→Some may want to do this every time a change is pushed, and others may want to only deploy when a specific release is tagged.
   100→### 404 handling
   101→
   102→mdBook automatically generates a 404 page to be used for broken links.
   103→The default output is a file named `404.html` at the root of the book.
   104→Some services like [GitHub Pages] will automatically use this page for broken links.
   105→For other services, you may want to consider configuring the web server to use this page as it will provide the reader navigation to get back to the book.
guide/src/for_developers/README.md
     1→# For developers
     2→
     3→While `mdbook` is mainly used as a command line tool, you can also import the
     4→underlying libraries directly and use those to manage a book. It also has a fairly
     5→flexible plugin mechanism, allowing you to create your own custom tooling and
     6→consumers (often referred to as *backends*) if you need to do some analysis of
     7→the book or render it in a different format.
    17→## The build process
    18→
    19→The process of rendering a book project goes through several steps.
    30→## Using `mdbook` as a library
    31→
    32→The `mdbook` binary is just a wrapper around the underlying mdBook crates,
    33→exposing their functionality as a command-line program. If you want to
    34→programmatically drive mdBook, you can use the [`mdbook-driver`] crate.
    35→This can be used to add your own functionality or tweak the build process.
guide/src/for_developers/backends.md
     1→# Alternative backends
     2→
     3→A "backend" is simply a program which `mdbook` will invoke during the book
     4→rendering process. This program is passed a JSON representation of the book and
     5→configuration information via `stdin`. Once the backend receives this
     6→information it is free to do whatever it wants.
    13→## Setting up
    14→
    15→This page will step you through creating your own alternative backend in the form
    16→of a simple word counting program. Although it will be written in Rust, there's
    17→no reason why it couldn't be accomplished using something like Python or Ruby.
    53→## Inspecting the book
    54→
    55→Now our backend has a copy of the book, lets count how many words are in each
    56→chapter!
    82→## Enabling the backend
    83→
    84→Now we've got the basics running, we want to actually use it. First, install the
    85→program.
   159→## Configuration
   160→
   161→Now imagine you don't want to count the number of words on a particular chapter
   162→(it might be generated text/code, etc). The canonical way to do this is via the
   163→usual `book.toml` configuration file by adding items to your `[output.foo]`
   164→table.
   219→## Output and signalling failure
   220→
   221→While it's nice to print word counts to the terminal when a book is built, it
   222→might also be a good idea to output them to a file somewhere. `mdbook` tells a
   223→backend where it should place any generated output via the `destination` field
   224→in [`RenderContext`].
   322→## Wrapping up
   323→
   324→Although contrived, hopefully this example was enough to show how you'd create
   325→an alternative backend for `mdbook`. If you feel it's missing something, don't
   326→hesitate to create an issue in the [issue tracker] so we can improve the user
   327→guide.
